            <!-- JE: Can this be right? An early modern humanist suggesting that words are corrupted by Latin? -->
            <!-- CG: This section of text is all about an intense debate at the beginning of the 16th century regarding 
            which vernacular language to employ for more serious literary endeavors. Castiglione is in favor of 
            a more courtly, spoken language, while his contemporaries prefer to use the Tuscan/Florentine
            language found in Petrarch and Boccaccio. In fact this section is Castiglione complaining about the 
            overly Latinate and unnatural sounding language of Boccaccio's Florentine.-->
